{"id":"2008.05887","submitter":"Boris Ivlev","authors":"Boris I. Ivlev","title":"Anomalous electron states and neutron emission","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Unexpected electron states in atom are proposed. The states are bound to the\nelectrostatic field of atomic nucleus cut off on its size. These anomalous\nstates are singular and thus non-physical. Under electron-photon interaction\nquantum fluctuations drive the singularity at various positions leading to its\ncut off. The resulting anomalous state becomes physical with the binding energy\nin the $MeV$ range. The state is assisted by a heavy photon cloud making its\ndirect creation impossible. In a solid under mechanical stress atoms jump to\nneighbour positions. The electron drag by the moving nucleus cuts the\nsingularity off even with no electron-photon interaction. The electron\ntransition to the formed anomalous state can directly activate nuclear\ndeformation modes. This results in neutron emission under mechanical stress.\nNature allows the anomalous neutron (anomalous electron bound to proton), which\nexhibits itself as stable and neutral Bose particle, of approximately neutron\nmass and size, and carrying non-zero baryon and lepton numbers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 3 Aug 2020 20:02:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 29 Nov 2020 23:24:14 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 23 Feb 2021 15:05:39 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 19 Aug 2021 22:05:28 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 25 Oct 2021 22:27:52 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Mon, 3 Jan 2022 18:05:35 GMT"},{"version":"v7","created":"Mon, 20 Jun 2022 12:01:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-22"}
